WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.860
Thanks for that introduction. I'm Amelia McNamara. I teach statistics at the University

00:00:12.860 --> 00:00:21.200
of St. Thomas in the Department of Computer Science. I tweet at AmeliaMN, which is a double

00:00:21.200 --> 00:00:27.080
entendre for McNamara and Minnesota. And I'm going to be talking about working with categorical

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:35.040
data in R without losing your mind. So this talk came from a paper that I wrote for the

00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:41.439
Practical Data Science for Stats Peer J Collection, which was organized by Jenny Bryan and Hadley

00:00:41.439 --> 00:00:46.880
Wickham. And if you haven't checked out this collection of papers yet, you really should,

00:00:46.880 --> 00:00:53.000
because it's extremely useful. There are all these wonderful papers like Data Organization

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:58.400
in Spreadsheets, Opinionated Analysis Development. Excuse me, do you have a moment to talk about

00:00:58.400 --> 00:01:03.400
version control? And then the paper that I worked on was called Wrangling Categorical

00:01:03.400 --> 00:01:10.080
Data in R. So all of these papers are fully reproducible. They're available online on

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:15.440
GitHub. Then they're on these sort of open source preprints on Peer J, and we did a special

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:22.860
issue of the American Statistician and put them in there as well. And my paper was inspired

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:28.419
by my work as a professor. So I teach a lot of introductory statistics classes, and in

00:01:28.419 --> 00:01:34.419
those classes I ask students to do projects where they go out in the world, they find

00:01:34.419 --> 00:01:40.820
real data, and then they analyze it, usually using some modeling, usually multiple regression.

00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:46.580
And this is a really useful exercise for students because they get the experience of working

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:51.860
with data that's real data that they hopefully care about. But it's very challenging for

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:56.940
them because they don't always have the skills to work with it. And it's also very challenging

00:01:56.940 --> 00:02:00.900
for me because when they don't have the skills to work with it or things are very complicated,

00:02:00.900 --> 00:02:06.019
then I step in and I'm there helping them do their data wrangling. So I always provide

00:02:06.019 --> 00:02:10.660
them with a list of ideas where they could go to look and find their data for their project,

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:15.740
but they go out and make the decision themselves, and then I help them make it work.

00:02:15.740 --> 00:02:20.500
So I had a group one year that wanted to use data from the General Social Survey, which

00:02:20.500 --> 00:02:27.940
is housed at the University of Chicago, which is the survey that's been going on since 1972

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:33.339
to ask questions about Americans about their life. So this is a data set that sociologists

00:02:33.339 --> 00:02:41.380
love to use. And it's very interesting, but it's filled with categorical variables. If

00:02:41.380 --> 00:02:45.539
you've been working in R or working with data, you probably know about categorical data.

00:02:45.539 --> 00:02:51.380
So that's as opposed to continuous data. It's something that has kind of discrete levels.

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:56.860
So you might think about gender as a categorical variable, male, female, non-binary. You could

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:01.460
think of more categories there. You could think about whether you like your coffee hot

00:03:01.460 --> 00:03:06.740
or cold. That could be a categorical variable. You could think about the colors of Skittles

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:14.660
on my front page. There's many types of data that end up being represented as categorical.

00:03:14.779 --> 00:03:21.899
When you have survey responses, those are often like I agree, I disagree. Race is often

00:03:21.899 --> 00:03:27.300
a categorical variable because we don't have some continuous spectrum there. So lots of

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:34.460
data has categorical variables. And in R, you probably know that we represent

00:03:34.460 --> 00:03:41.419
categorical data as factors. And factors consist of a set of values and then an ordered set

00:03:41.419 --> 00:03:51.820
of valid levels. And when I started thinking about the paper that I was going to write,

00:03:51.820 --> 00:03:55.979
I was thinking about all these problems that come up when you're doing data wrangling in

00:03:55.979 --> 00:04:01.779
real data problems from this experience of working with my students. And so I said, you

00:04:01.779 --> 00:04:07.020
know, I could write a paper on a couple different subjects, but here's one, you know, I could

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:13.100
talk about factors and how to recode them. And so this is in May 2016, so I'm fresh out

00:04:13.100 --> 00:04:18.260
of projects and I've been thinking about how hard it was to do the work with factor variables

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:23.779
specifically on this project with the students who are working with the GSS data.

00:04:23.779 --> 00:04:28.859
And you know, on this GitHub issue, people said, ah, that first idea sounds okay. Second

00:04:28.859 --> 00:04:33.540
one is really good. So that's the one that I started working on.

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:39.739
So in June, you know, I start writing this paper and thinking about the ways that you

00:04:39.739 --> 00:04:45.579
can work with factor variables and do analysis in a principled way so that you don't end

00:04:45.579 --> 00:04:52.339
up wrecking your data. And eventually this became the paper Wrangling Categorical Data

00:04:52.339 --> 00:04:58.980
in R, which has me and then also Nick Horton from Amherst College. He has the best Twitter

00:04:58.980 --> 00:05:04.820
handle, Ask Dr. Stats. So we wrote this paper and you can go read it. If it's worrying you

00:05:04.820 --> 00:05:10.200
that it says in red not peer reviewed, you can go read it at the American Statistician

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:15.739
where it has been peer reviewed and code reviewed. So it's all good.

00:05:15.739 --> 00:05:22.299
So we started off this paper by showing some of the ways in which factors behave unexpectedly.

00:05:22.299 --> 00:05:27.459
So one of the ways is that if you have some numeric data and you turn it into a factor,

00:05:27.459 --> 00:05:31.440
it sort of looks the same because it has those same values, but then it has the levels

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:37.260
associated with it. And if you convert back to a numeric, then you don't get the numbers

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:44.100
that you expect. Okay? So instead of getting back 20, 20, 10, 40, 10, I get back 2, 2,

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:49.459
1, 3, 1. And this is the sort of thing that can really mess you up when you're doing analysis

00:05:49.459 --> 00:05:58.940
with factors. Because you think that you're going to get back the value, but you get back

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:04.859
sort of the numeric level instead. There's other things like this where, you know, if

00:06:04.859 --> 00:06:09.540
you create a factor variable and give levels that don't match, you're going to get an NA.

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:15.540
Again, you don't get a warning or a message or an error. If I had saved this into an object,

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:21.459
it just would have seemed like it worked, but I've lost that level of A. So there are

00:06:21.459 --> 00:06:26.339
things like this that you learn to kind of work around when you're working with factor

00:06:26.339 --> 00:06:31.820
data. And I think these frustrating issues were

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:38.299
much more common back in the days of Yore when we were using read.csv to read in our

00:06:38.299 --> 00:06:45.420
data files. Because read.csv has this argument of strings as factors, and that was by default

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:51.420
set to true. So any time you had any character or string variable, it was getting read in

00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:57.100
as a factor. And so people were running into these frustrating issues a lot.

00:06:57.100 --> 00:07:03.179
Roger Peng has a great blog post that's strings as factors, an unauthorized biography, and

00:07:03.179 --> 00:07:09.660
he talks about some of the historical reasons why this default was set to be true. And I

00:07:09.660 --> 00:07:14.459
think the most salient one is that it used to save space in memory. So instead of having

00:07:14.459 --> 00:07:20.660
to save in quotes, you know, like high, medium, low, many, many times as strings, it would

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:26.220
save one, two, three, the numerals many times, and then just keep those labels once. It turns

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:34.299
out that even base R is no longer doing that, so it's not a memory or storage issue anymore.

00:07:34.299 --> 00:07:41.260
But people were getting frustrated with strings as factors not defaulting to false. This led

00:07:41.260 --> 00:07:48.299
to the strings as factors equal hell no movement. At JSM one year, I think Jenny Bryan made

00:07:48.459 --> 00:07:55.459
these ribbons that you could put on your name tag to represent how you felt about that issue.

00:07:56.540 --> 00:08:03.339
And so when we moved into the tidyverse kind of world where people are using read underscore

00:08:03.339 --> 00:08:08.940
CSV, that got baked into the philosophy that you shouldn't be forcing some data format

00:08:08.940 --> 00:08:15.019
on your string or character vectors, because that might not be what you want, and you could

00:08:15.019 --> 00:08:20.619
run into these icky issues where things can get disconnected in a strange way. So now

00:08:20.619 --> 00:08:27.019
if you read underscore CSV, you're not going to encounter factors that much anymore.

00:08:27.019 --> 00:08:33.380
So the problem is you sometimes still need factors. We can't get rid of them altogether.

00:08:33.380 --> 00:08:38.500
In particular, if you're doing modeling, even just using a simple linear model, but you're

00:08:38.500 --> 00:08:43.900
including a categorical variable, a factor variable in your analysis, those need to be

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:49.539
formatted as factors so that you can choose which level is your reference level. And you

00:08:49.539 --> 00:08:56.539
can't do that with character strings because R will just pick the first level alphabetically.

00:08:57.059 --> 00:09:02.500
You also need to work with factors if you want to reorder elements that are maybe in

00:09:02.500 --> 00:09:07.580
your ggplot. So if you have a number of items on your plot and you want them in some other

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:14.539
order, you need those to be factors so that you can reorder them properly.

00:09:14.539 --> 00:09:20.299
So we still need to use factors, and up until reasonably recently, this meant doing a bunch

00:09:20.299 --> 00:09:27.059
of ugly base R code. So this is an example of some ugly base R code that I wrote for

00:09:27.059 --> 00:09:33.580
another fully reproducible journal article in 2013. So if you want to look at some vintage

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:40.059
R code, I recommend it. This paper will maybe come out this year, so it's now six years

00:09:40.059 --> 00:09:46.820
old and it's really getting pretty classic. So if you remember working with factors, this

00:09:46.820 --> 00:09:52.140
is the sort of thing that you would be doing, right? You'd be overriding the levels or you'd

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:58.700
be reordering the levels by using square brackets and the C function to reorder them.

00:09:58.859 --> 00:10:05.140
So this code actually is probably going to show up looking very similar to a bad approach

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:10.820
piece of code that I have in a minute. I did check it, and this one happens to be working

00:10:10.820 --> 00:10:15.340
properly, but I actually think that in this paper, if you go look at the code, probably

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:20.979
I've messed up some of my factors and my analysis is wrong as a result.

00:10:20.979 --> 00:10:29.900
So R users love to talk about how Excel forces data to be dates, for example. When you open

00:10:29.900 --> 00:10:36.099
a spreadsheet, then anything that looks vaguely like a date becomes a date. But R has similar

00:10:36.099 --> 00:10:42.700
issues where factors can ruin your data in sort of a horrifying way.

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:50.260
So in the paper that Nick Horton and I wrote, we were focusing on the GSS data, and so what

00:10:50.260 --> 00:10:55.380
we showed were some of the bad approaches that you can use in base R. So if you have

00:10:55.380 --> 00:11:05.500
a variable about income and you want to order this so that it's in an appropriate order,

00:11:05.500 --> 00:11:12.500
right? We want far above average to come first, and then above average, average, et cetera,

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:15.900
one thing that you can do is overwrite the levels. So that's what I was doing just a

00:11:15.900 --> 00:11:20.659
minute ago, and you can watch and you can see how this is wrecking my data. So watch

00:11:20.659 --> 00:11:32.419
like average, about 1,000 observations, and now average 666, okay? So because I'm overwriting

00:11:32.419 --> 00:11:39.059
the levels outside of the factor command, I've now broken the relationship between my

00:11:39.059 --> 00:11:43.979
levels and labels, and all of my data is now invalid. And again, it's not going to give

00:11:43.979 --> 00:11:49.780
you an error or a warning. Another bad approach in base R, again, you

00:11:49.780 --> 00:11:56.099
could watch the average category, is you use the levels there and do it numerically in

00:11:56.099 --> 00:12:01.020
some way. So again, this is looking similar to my code that I was showing, except I think

00:12:01.020 --> 00:12:08.859
mine happened to continue to work. And so Nick and I, you know, said you shouldn't be

00:12:08.859 --> 00:12:13.780
using this kind of base R code. If you're going to use base R, you should be using a

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:22.380
more robust approach. So you should be doing something where you're going to use the factor

00:12:22.380 --> 00:12:29.580
command, you're going to put levels within it, and now things are working much better.

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:38.460
If you watch, for example, above average 483, that count is going to stay appropriate, right?

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:43.619
But something has happened to average. Average actually did not come through. Even though

00:12:43.619 --> 00:12:50.460
I'm using a more robust base R approach, I'm still losing my average values because I made

00:12:50.460 --> 00:12:56.940
a typo. I put a trailing space after the word average when I was recoding my levels.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:13:03.820
So we called this a fragile approach, sort of a reference to the idea of software brittleness,

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:10.460
where if one little thing changes, then your code can break. And so we're thinking about

00:13:10.460 --> 00:13:17.580
if you had a collaborator who sent you a new spreadsheet and they happened to change the

00:13:17.580 --> 00:13:24.179
phrasing of one of the levels, or if you are a little bit fat fingering and you hit a space,

00:13:24.179 --> 00:13:30.299
then you're going to, again, mess up your data. But this approach at least is not losing

00:13:30.299 --> 00:13:35.739
the counts for everything. It's just that one place where I made the typo.

00:13:35.739 --> 00:13:44.260
So we're writing this paper. We're working on it. It's May, June, July of 2016. We're

00:13:44.260 --> 00:13:52.340
saying here are some bad approaches and here are the more robust or better base R approaches.

00:13:52.340 --> 00:13:57.340
And then if you've been following the tidyverse, you probably know the thing that happens next,

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:03.539
which is that Hadley writes forecasts. So I've been talking to Hadley Wickham about

00:14:03.539 --> 00:14:09.979
the problems with factor variables for a while. And my suspicion is that when he saw me working

00:14:09.979 --> 00:14:14.820
on this paper where I wrote out some of these very specific issues and the ways that they

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:19.340
probably needed to be solved, that that was just what he needed to say now I'm actually

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:23.260
going to implement this package. And you'll see the inspiration there because the dataset

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:30.099
that comes with forecasts is also GSS. So my students' choice of final project data

00:14:30.099 --> 00:14:36.020
I think is having far-reaching implications. So he wrote this package, and it's fantastic

00:14:36.020 --> 00:14:40.820
because it solves a huge number of the issues that were happening when you were working

00:14:40.820 --> 00:14:48.979
with factors in base R. So if you haven't used it before, you must use it. It has functions

00:14:48.979 --> 00:14:55.380
like re-code, re-level, reorder, collapse, lump, other. So it can do a lot of these tasks

00:14:55.380 --> 00:15:01.859
that you would often want to do with categorical data without wrecking it in a much more human

00:15:01.859 --> 00:15:12.619
understandable way. So with those base R approaches, a lot of it is putting the onus on the programmer.

00:15:12.619 --> 00:15:17.140
You as the person who's doing the data analysis have to remember what the levels are. You

00:15:17.140 --> 00:15:22.739
have to make sure that you're not getting a space. You have to kind of do this process

00:15:22.739 --> 00:15:27.340
where you go back and forth between the data and your code, and you have to be very careful

00:15:27.340 --> 00:15:32.659
that you're doing the right thing. So Brett Victor talks about how much cognitive load

00:15:32.659 --> 00:15:37.659
it takes to program when you're changing things and holding the information in your head.

00:15:37.659 --> 00:15:44.099
So forecasts is helping fix a lot of that. And this actually gave us a great opportunity

00:15:44.099 --> 00:15:48.299
for this paper that we'd written. We did have to go back and rewrite a huge amount

00:15:48.299 --> 00:15:55.460
of it. So thanks, Hadley. But I'm very interested in the variety of R syntaxes that exist. So

00:15:55.460 --> 00:16:00.020
I have this cheat sheet, which is a contributed cheat sheet on RStudio. So scroll down to

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:05.619
the bottom. And it compares doing the same task in what I consider to be the three main

00:16:05.619 --> 00:16:11.619
syntaxes in R. The dollar sign syntax, which is kind of standard base R, the formula syntax,

00:16:11.619 --> 00:16:17.140
and the tidyverse syntax. When I teach, I try and stay away from that base R syntax.

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:22.859
I was team formula syntax for a long time. So that's the mosaic package and lattice graphics.

00:16:22.859 --> 00:16:26.500
And now I've been pretty convinced to move over to the tidyverse syntax, because I think

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:30.940
it removes more of that stuff you have to hold in your head as a programmer.

00:16:30.940 --> 00:16:36.580
So what this allowed us to do, the development of forecasts with our paper, is compare several

00:16:36.580 --> 00:16:42.020
different methods for the same problem. So we often show like a compact but fragile way

00:16:42.020 --> 00:16:48.340
to do things with base R. We show a more robust but verbose, like many lines and very repetitive

00:16:48.340 --> 00:16:54.179
coding solution in base R. And then we show the direct and robust solution from the tidyverse.

00:16:54.179 --> 00:17:00.460
So with that data about your opinion of income, again, you could watch average or below average.

00:17:00.460 --> 00:17:06.380
You're going to relevel that factor. Now everything's in the right order and the counts are right.

00:17:06.380 --> 00:17:11.739
And forecasts has lots of good defaults. So in some functions, if you don't provide

00:17:11.739 --> 00:17:15.660
all the factor levels, it just sticks the rest of them at the end, or it'll give you

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:22.939
good errors and warnings. So it's fixed a lot of this stuff.

00:17:22.939 --> 00:17:28.300
Another example, if you did this in base and you wanted to collapse the marital status,

00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:32.420
you could do something like this. I think this is actually working, but it really counts

00:17:32.420 --> 00:17:37.900
on you as the analyst, being able to count the indices of, you know, divorced comes first

00:17:37.900 --> 00:17:43.619
and then married and then never married, no answer. And if the data changes in some way,

00:17:43.619 --> 00:17:48.619
like if your collaborator decides to move something around, it's going to break.

00:17:48.619 --> 00:17:54.979
But the tidyverse solution using recode is much neater, and it will actually work in

00:17:54.979 --> 00:18:01.060
a larger variety of situations. So part of my, the goal of this talk is to

00:18:01.060 --> 00:18:06.939
evangelize for forecasts and the tidyverse and get you to use it.

00:18:06.939 --> 00:18:12.500
I think there's also something to be said about defensive coding here. So the way that

00:18:12.500 --> 00:18:17.500
you make sure that your examples are working is you have to, like, look at your data over

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:24.859
and over again. So this is from an issue on that same paper. This was someone's example

00:18:24.859 --> 00:18:29.420
that had to do with categorical data, factor data, splitting the data into testing and

00:18:29.420 --> 00:18:35.939
training data. You can get different factor levels in the two datasets, and then, again,

00:18:35.939 --> 00:18:39.819
when you do the modeling and the predictions, it won't throw an error, but everything is

00:18:39.819 --> 00:18:44.579
going to be wrong. So there's lots of ways that working with factors can go wrong.

00:18:44.579 --> 00:18:51.060
And so one of your methods of defense is just summary, summary, summary. So you saw every

00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:54.900
one of those examples, I ran the summary first, then I did something with my factors, and

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:58.900
then I ran it again. And you could use count or something from the tidyverse if you wanted

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:02.619
to. This is just a little more compact to show on the screen.

00:19:02.619 --> 00:19:08.939
The other thing that we talked about is maybe you could get some testing worked into your

00:19:08.939 --> 00:19:13.859
paper, right? So you have the number of levels, assert that the level should be equal, equal

00:19:13.859 --> 00:19:19.099
to three, or test that the levels should be female and male, just so that you can keep

00:19:19.099 --> 00:19:26.579
track of your analysis. Expect equivalent doesn't work if the levels are the right levels,

00:19:26.579 --> 00:19:33.780
but out of order, so that's on my wish list for future versions of the package.

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:39.180
And so my takeaways from this talk are essentially that you should use forecasts. That's going

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:45.660
to solve the vast majority of your problems. But like I said with the testing and training

00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:50.339
dataset, it doesn't always solve every single problem, so you really need to be practicing

00:19:50.339 --> 00:19:56.699
defensive coding. And that probably means that summary is your friend, and maybe you

00:19:56.699 --> 00:20:01.900
want to be asserting that and testing that things in your analysis. And if you want to

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:07.020
see more horror stories and have a good way to explain to people why the tidyverse is

00:20:07.020 --> 00:20:12.420
better, not just for people and their thinking, but actually for making your data work, that's

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.219
the paper, and thank you very much.

